once you get attached to a group of people, you have so much invested in your "relationship" with them. This series did an amazing job of making every character real. I won't go into the details, (to avoid spoilers) but I would have liked certain things to turn out differently. It was awesome to spend 6 years with these people, especially all the kids, to see them literally grow up.

It's still very good actors/producers are trying to hard to get it all in because They know it's going to be the last season. Wish there was less Max, more Julia, and Crosby.  Let Zeke be  Zeke.  Cantakerous, loud iand back on his feet.

Well my husband and I finally started watching this show after it had actually ended.  Watched all 6 seasons in about a 9 month time span, and we just kept waiting for it to be so awesome.  We had heard all this great stuff, and people acting incredulous when they found out that we had never seen it.  Maybe it was just too hyped up for us, or maybe it truly is a series meant to be seen only once a week for a few months of the year over a six year time period.  Many of the characters just got so annoying to us, and there was always, always so much drama.  I get that there is drama in real life, and the family and sibling dynamic, yada, yada, yada, but this was an unreal amount of drama for one family.  A yuppie, upper middle class, liberal, Berkely, granola family.  Now the original movie that this series is based on from 1989 with Steve Martin? Now THAT is fantastic, and I highly recommend!

Each season of this show was exceptional, thoughtful, emotional, and personal. Season 6 is a magnificent conclusion to a series of intertwined stories that loyal viewers have enjoyed from beginning to end. Every person can relate to at least one of the characters, and many of the situations the chracters find themselves in.

This is not a classic feel-good show by any means, but it delivers a positive emotional experience. It exposes the raw nerves of emotion, struggle, pain, and regret. It features bad choices and gut-wrenching consequences. However, what makes this show a work of genius is its ability to find the joy, happiness, and acceptance of all aspects of life, good and bad - and the show certainly includes ample portions of good times amidst the tragic. The Bravermans are a tight-knit family, who have their share of scraps among themselves, but never forget who they are and where they come from.

Mo member of the extended family is spared from heartache. You'd think a show loaded with divorce, infidelity, Aspergers, cancer, heart disease, job loss, teen pregnancy, failing business, death, and more, would be a major downer. But the show was able to find peace and joy in the struggle, in overcoming obstacles.

The final season, and certainly the final episode, did not disappoint its fan base. It's one of the great finales in the history of TV. They clearly took the time and care to end the series with grace and dignity, sorrow and joy (mostly joy). The fact that is hasn't won or even been nominated for an Emmy (Best Drama Series) is an injustice. It stands tall against anything HBO, Showtime, AMC, and other networks have produced over its 6 year run..

If there is one defining message, it's that you should be true to yourself, and by living that philosophy, despite some likely short term pain in doing so, you'll be on the best path to true happiness.

This is a really good show, with excellent story telling, great character development, and it pulls no punches about the highs and lows of being a parent.  In fact, it would easily have earned the rare (for me) 5 stars, but for two intensely annoying choices by the creators: first, the song during the opening credits is an almost comically bad example of the worst Bob Dylan can do to a song (and this is from someone who really likes Bob Dylan); in the 5th season, they canned the offending song in favor of something much more tolerable, seeming to recognize how atrocious it was, but then they stupidly brought it back for the final season!  Second, the writers have some kind of fetish for having characters talk over each other.  Yes, it sometimes happens in the real world, but when they have it happen in nearly every episode, it gets pretty annoying.  Overall, we still really enjoyed the show, and I recommend it, but the creators need to develop some insight and concern for their audience before doing another show.

I thought about inventing a drinking game involving shots anytime Amber cries, but I'd probably develop a liver disorder. I've watched the entire series except the last episode. This show, in concept and execution, is among the very best television series ever produced.  That it was the recipient of few, if any, awards does not diminish its artistry; but, sadly, exposes how inconsequential the self-acclaimed "experts" in programming quality have become.  The greatness of "Parenthood's" legacy will, we believe, continue to grow in the years ahead... and it is a fitting tribute that its six seasons will now become a treasured part of DVD collections--to be viewed again and again; and, especially important, made available to those who did not have an opportunity to experience the artistry of "Parenthood" when it originally aired.  Congratulations to everyone who was responsible in the creation of this extraordinary event!  --Ron & Renee Howe / Erskine, Minnesota

Just one episode in and one can tell that this will be a fitting farewell to the Braverman family after six much-loved seasons. I first started watching this show on my brother's recommendation in 2010 and was immediately hooked. It is brilliantly scripted and acted, always ringing true. The actors speak what seems to be real dialogue in a realistic manner often interrupting and speaking over one another. I don't know about your family, but that is exactly what mine does. There are two aging parents and four adult children, each with their own families. These characters seem real, flaws and all. The plots never stoop to a soap opera level they are always true to life and topical. And while many current issues in modern life are played out, it does not seem like a season of Oprah, everything is done with a light hand. This season seems to be no exception. In the first episode we pick up where they left off last season with just enough time passing to have brought about the changes hinted at previously. One actually cares about this fictional family, and while it will be sad to see them go, I'm sure that this last season will bring closure and resolution.

Parenthood is one of the finest shows to ever air on network television. The writing is second to none, and the characters are as real as they get. The series breaks new ground with every episode, and captures real life situations in a way never seen before on network TV. It's a rarity to see topical issues treated in such a fair and honest way, all with a wonderful blend of drama, humor and insight.

With each episode, my wife and I feel as if we're a part of this incredible family. While I'm happy that it was renewed for an abbreviated sixth season, I'm sad that it won't be around for a seventh. In my opinion, this series is ending way before the story is fully told.
